initial_story: having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost,optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate foraccelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes aremodulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phasesare still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carryinformation for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose aframework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating inputimage data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input andoutput parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude andphase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures isintroduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that theproposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracywithin an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33%accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area isreduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.
stories: Optical neural networks have the potential to excel in processing tasks due to their capabilities of high speed, high throughput, and low energy expenditure. Conventionally, ONNs modulate light amplitudes at the input and output but ignore the phases, even though these can be used in computations as well. To rectify this, we introduce OplixNet, a framework that minimizes ONNs by encoding input image data into light signal amplitudes and phases. The redesigned network utilizes both amplitude and phase information and introduces mutual learning across ONN structures to preserve accuracy. Experimental results show that OplixNet significantly reduces ONN areas while maintaining acceptably high accuracy, with specific examples including 75.03% area reduction with 0.33% accuracy decrease in FCNN and 74.88% area reduction with 2.38% accuracy decrease in ResNet-32.

Our new optical neural network (OplixNet) improves ONN capabilities by utilizing both amplitude and phase information from input and output light signals. Conventionally, ONNs focus solely on amplitude adjustments, overlooking phase data, which can also be exploited. Our redesigned network, while maintaining accuracy, cuts ONN processing areas significantly, achieving 75.03% reduction with a 0.33% accuracy loss for FCNN and 74.88% reduction with a 2.38% accuracy decrease for ResNet-32, making OplixNet an innovative solution for fast, energy-efficient processing tasks.
